<subSubSection id="49C942EEFF8A3952EBD2C53CFB30594F" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="016C1165FF8A3952EBD2C53CFEAA591F" blockId="36.[227,1436,527,633]" box="[227,341,527,553]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<heading id="5A24A609FF8A3952EBD2C53CFEAA591F" bold="true" box="[227,341,527,553]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" reason="3">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF8A3952EBD2C53CFEAA591F" bold="true" box="[227,341,527,553]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="016C1165FF8A3952EBD2C508FB30594F" blockId="36.[227,1436,527,633]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
Compared to other otoliths of 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF8A3952E963C50FFD215963" authorityName="Kanazawa" authorityYear="1961" box="[594,734,572,597]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Congridae" genus="Paraconger" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anguilliformes" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF8A3952E963C50FFD215963" box="[594,734,572,597]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Paraconger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, otoliths of 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FF8A3952E842C50FFBA35963" authorityName="Muller" authorityYear="1999" box="[883,1116,571,597]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Congridae" genus="Paraconger" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anguilliformes" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="solidus">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FF8A3952E842C50FFBA35963" box="[883,1116,571,597]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Paraconger solidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the most compact and highest-shaped ones. The species seems to be restricted to the Piney Point Formation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
